{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01U85MaKaYFD6RV3D181SmSg","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\n\n## Code Review Summary\n\n**Story:** 11-2-workflow-referential-integrity-validation\n**Issues Found:** 2 High, 1 Medium, 2 Low\n**Issues Fixed:** 2 High, 1 Medium\n\n### Fixed Issues\n\n**HIGH-1: Silent error swallowing in agent validation catch block** (`workflow-parser.ts:96-100`)\nThe bare `catch {}` around `resolveAgent()` silently swallowed ALL errors, treating corrupt YAML, schema failures, and I/O errors identically to \"agent not found\". Fixed by distinguishing `AgentResolveError` with \"Embedded agent not found:\" prefix from other failure modes, and reporting the actual error message for non-\"not-found\" cases.\n\n**HIGH-2: Unexpected errors silently discarded** (`workflow-parser.ts:96-100`)\nNon-`AgentResolveError` exceptions (e.g., unexpected runtime errors) were silently caught and turned into misleading \"not found\" messages. Fixed by adding a fallback catch that reports the actual error.\n\n**MEDIUM-1: Dead parameter `_taskNames` in `validateReferentialIntegrity`** (`workflow-parser.ts:70`)\nThe `_taskNames: Set<string>` parameter was accepted but never used. Removed it from the function signature and call site.\n\n### Files Modified\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/workflow-parser.ts` — error handling fix, dead param removal, new import\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/src/lib/__tests__/workflow-parser.test.ts` — 1 new test for error message format\n- `/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/11-2-workflow-referential-integrity-validation.md` — status to `verifying`\n\n### Verification\n- Build: zero TypeScript errors\n- Tests: 4351 passed, 0 failed (164 test files)\n- Coverage: 96.69% overall, all 167 files above 80% floor\n\n---\n\n## Session Issues\n\n**Bugs found:**\n- HIGH: Bare catch block in `validateReferentialIntegrity` silently swallowed all errors from `resolveAgent()`, including corrupt YAML and schema failures, treating them as \"not found\" -- FIXED\n- HIGH: Non-AgentResolveError exceptions silently discarded with misleading error message -- FIXED\n- MEDIUM: Dead `_taskNames` parameter in `validateReferentialIntegrity` function signature -- FIXED\n\n**Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW):**\n- LOW: `resolveAgent()` is called at parse time for every task with an `agent` field, performing full resolution (file reads, schema validation, patch application). This is heavier than needed for an existence check. A lighter `agentExists(name)` function would be more appropriate, but the performance impact is negligible given typical workflow sizes (2-5 tasks).\n- LOW: `resolveAgent()` defaults `cwd` to `process.cwd()` when called from validation, which may not match the workflow file's directory for project-level custom agents. Not a problem for embedded agents (the primary use case).\n\n**Coverage gaps:**\n- The \"found but broken\" agent error path (lines 104-109 in fixed code) is not covered by unit tests because mocking ES module exports requires vitest's `vi.mock()` at the top level, which would change the test file structure significantly. The path is structurally correct but untested. This is an acceptable gap for now.\n- No integration test for agent validation when both user-level and project-level custom agents exist simultaneously.\n\n**Architecture concerns:**\n- None. The implementation follows established patterns (collect errors, throw once) and respects module boundaries (uses registry API, not driver internals).\n\n**Items sent back for re-development:**\n- None.\n\n## Token Report\n\n- Total tool calls: 20\n- By tool: Bash: 7, Read: 9, Edit: 4, Grep: 1, Glob: 1, Skill: 1, Write: 0, other: 0\n- Largest Bash outputs (top 3 by line count): `npm run test:unit --reporter=verbose` (~80 lines), `npm run test:unit` (~20 lines x2)\n- Files read: 9 unique, 12 total reads (workflow-parser.test.ts read 4 times due to size limits)\n- Redundant operations: workflow-parser.test.ts required 4 partial reads due to the 10k token limit; could have been optimized to 3 reads with better offset planning. Two near-identical test runs after the failed mock test could have been avoided with a better testing strategy upfront."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a4ea645a2f78958f3 (use SendMessage with to: 'a4ea645a2f78958f3' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 72102\ntool_uses: 38\nduration_ms: 277007</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4b1f7711-6ed7-4488-a0af-b261e761b450","uuid":"d9aadff8-37e9-402f-a8d2-70c29a0c8811","timestamp":"2026-04-03T08:41:12.441Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Run /bmad-code-review for the story at _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/11-2-workflow-referential-integrity-validation.md — perform adversarial review, fix all HIGH and MEDIUM issues found. After fixing, run `codeharness coverage --min-file 80` and ensure all files pass the per-file floor and the overall 90% target. Update the story status to `verifying` when all issues are fixed and coverage passes. Do NOT ask the user any questions — proceed autonomously. Do NOT run git commit. Do NOT run git add. Do NOT modify sprint-status.yaml.\n\nMANDATORY — End your response with a `## Session Issues` section listing:\n- Bugs found and their severity (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW with brief description)\n- Code quality issues found but NOT fixed (LOW priority items, tech debt)\n- Coverage gaps (files below floor, untested edge cases, areas needing integration tests)\n- Architecture concerns (patterns that don't fit, coupling issues, missing abstractions)\n- Items sent back for re-development (what failed and why)\nIf nothing to report, write `## Session Issues\\n\\nNone.`\n\nMANDATORY — Also end your response with a `## Token Report` section:\n- Total tool calls: N\n- By tool: Bash: X, Read: Y, Edit: Z, Grep: W, Write: V, other: N\